20. dedicet Hebro. In plain words, ‘throw away‚’ as in the next Ode, ‘Tradam protervis in mare Creticum Portare ventis’; but the river seems to be chosen as one specially associated by Roman poets with images of winter (Epp. 1. 3. 3, 1. 16. 13, Virg. E. 10. 65, Aen. 12. 331), and so one to which the offering of withered leaves is more appropriate.
